The engine may be turned off, the FAA has ordered the inspection of 2000 Boeing passenger aircraft.
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring emergency inspections of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737 Classic aircraft registered in the United States, due to the corrosion of the air check valve of the aircraft, which may cause the engine to stop in the air after the corrosion.
The FAA said it has received four reports of air parking of 737NG and 737 Classic aircraft engines so far, resulting in emergency inspections of passenger aircraft that have been parked for seven days or more and aircraft that have flown less than 11 times so far after re-opening flights.
The Federal Aviation Administration warned that if the fifth-stage check valve for all two engines of the passenger aircraft was corroded, it may die in the open position, causing the passenger plane to lose power completely and unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the airline must replace the key component before the passenger plane is put into service again.
Boeing responded later in the day, the outbreak of the new crown epidemic led to lower travel demand, many passenger aircraft were sealed or less used, "return valve is more likely to be corroded."
Boeing also said that it has advised air operators to inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the instructions, and if problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in overhauling and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that passenger aircraft of major U.S. airlines usually fly multiple times in a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown epidemic, a large number of passenger aircraft were grounded; with the recent slow growth in passenger travel demand, some passenger aircraft have been put back into operation.
The FAA did not release details of the four aerial parking reports.
Alaska Airlines later disclosed one of the incidents.
The airline said in a statement that a passenger plane was flying from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas, on July 15, when an engine suddenly turned off, and the passenger plane finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the engine and had inspected the engines of six aircraft in accordance with FAA directives.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that their passenger aircraft did not have the engine shutdown associated with the air check valve.
Four American Airlines planes will be inspected, and 28 United Airlines planes will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 aircraft, but did not say whether there had been an engine shutdown.
According to multiple media reports, the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive is another shock to Boeing.
A Boeing 737 MAX passenger aircraft from Lion Air Indonesia and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019, respectively, killing 346 people.
The series of passenger aircraft was subsequently grounded worldwide, discontinued in January this year, and resumed production in May.
FAA Administrator Steve Dixon acknowledged in June that the FAA had “made a mistake” in its oversight of Boeing over the 737 MAX.
