For the first time, the United States launched a countervailing investigation on China with "undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate"
In response to the recent announcement of the US Department of Commerce, it decided to launch an anti-dumping anti-subsidy investigation on belt (beam belt) products originating in China, and launched an investigation on the "RMB exchange rate undervaluation" project.
China's Ministry of Commerce pointed out that this is the first time that the United States has investigated the so-called "RMB exchange rate undervaluation" project in the countervailing case, and China firmly opposes it.
China's Ministry of Commerce issued a special press release on the evening of the 23rd, saying that China implements a floating exchange rate system based on market supply and demand, with reference to a basket of currencies for adjustment, and the market plays a decisive role in the formation of exchange rates.
The press release stressed that in general, the RMB exchange rate is at a reasonable equilibrium level and is not undervalued.
Since 2005, the RMB has appreciated by more than 17% against the US dollar.
According to the data released by the Bank for International Settlements, from the beginning of 2005 to May 2020, the effective exchange rate of the RMB project appreciated by 38%, and the real effective exchange rate appreciated by 49%, which is the strongest currency in the G20 economy and one of the largest in the world.
The Ministry of Commerce pointed out that the exchange rate issue exceeds the competence of members to conduct countervailing investigations in accordance with the rules of the World Trade Organization.
In February this year, the United States amended its regulations to conduct countervailing investigations on other countries' exchange rates, and has been suspected of violating WTO rules and has been opposed by many parties.
According to the press release, even in accordance with U.S. regulations, there are a large number of errors in the content of the applicant's complaint, and there are no necessary elements of countervailing subsidies such as financial support, benefit award and exportionism.
China urges the US to abide by existing international rules and stop conducting countervailing investigations into the so-called “undervaluation of the RMB exchange rate”.
Affected by the further escalation of tensions between China and the United States, the exchange rate of the offshore and onshore RMB against the US dollar fell sharply on the 22nd, and both fell below the 7.0 yuan mark of 1 US dollar against the RMB.
Whether the US Department of Commerce is intended to force the rise of the yuan is worth paying attention to.
The RMB against the US dollar rose above the 7.0 mark on the 23rd and closed at 6.9961.
The middle price of the RMB against the US dollar, which is regulated by the official, was lowered by 17 basic points on the 24th, at 6.9938.
