Lewis family: John Lewis is the fighter who 'fights the weakest'
U.S. Congressman John Lewis, a civil rights fighter, was remembered as a fighter for “fighting for the weakest” at a memorial service for him on Saturday.
Lewis' public memorial service has been held in Alabama since Saturday.
There were two memorials on the first day.
At a public memorial service at Troy University in Alabama on Saturday, five of Lewis’ siblings and a nephew spoke of him as a loving, timid, family-heavy man.
Lewis' youngest brother, Henry "Grant" Lewis, said at the meeting: "He has dedicated his life to helping others."
Samuel Lewis said his mother had warned John "not to get into trouble, not to get into trouble."
He added that John did not heed his mother’s warning, saying, “We all know that John always gets into trouble and always gets in trouble, but that’s because he sticks to the right thing, and that’s a good trouble.”
Lewis’s siblings reminded the people at the memorial service that John’s most famous argument was to create “good trouble,” that is, to avoid stirring up trouble for the sake of justice.
John applied to Troy University in Troy, Alabama, where he was born, but the all-white school at Troy University rejected his application.
John Lewis, who preached the gospel to chickens on his farm as a child, eventually earned a degree in religion and philosophy from Fisk University.
Years later, the University of Troy awarded Lewis an honorary doctorate.
Senator Doug Jones, from Alabama, said the current protesters were “provocating peacefully, non-violently,” as Lewis did during the civil rights movement.
Jones said: “Even if President Trump overturned a boat man with a pole and told all the protesters as thugs, he was wrong.
The protesters are patriots who want the United States to move towards a more equal country.”
A six-day series of events in honor of Lewis will culminate this week at a funeral in Georgia.
Lewis' coffin was parked in public memorials at the University of Troy on Saturday, and people came to pay tribute to the civil rights movement pioneer.
Later on Saturday, a private ceremony was held in a chapel in Selma, Alabama, followed by a public memorial service.
On Sunday, Lewis' body will pass through the Edmund Pettus Bridge in Selma.
In 1965, he and the demonstrators who demanded black voting rights were beaten by the Alabama police in front of the bridge, who also threw tear gas at demonstrators.
Lewis was nearly killed.
It was called Bloody Sunday.
Lewis' body will be transported to Montgomery, Alabama's capital.
Mayor Steven Reed encouraged people to line up on the sidewalk and finish the final journey with Lewis.
At the same time, officials require the public to wear masks and maintain social distance when participating in the event.
Alabama Gov. Kay Ivey ordered the flag to be flown at half-time on Saturday and Sunday in honor of Lewis.
During the nearly week-long commemoration, Lewis' body will be divided into the Alabama State Capitol in Montgomery, the Georgia State Capitol in Atlanta, and the U.S. Capitol in Washington, D.C., for public mourning.
U.S. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell announced last week that people could go to the U.S. Capitol on Monday and Tuesday to pay tribute to Lewis.
