APEC Trade Ministers Meeting Says It Will Accelerate Regional Economic Recovery
KUALA LUMPUR, July 25 (Xinhua) -- APEC member trade ministers held a video conference on the 25th, pledging to work to reduce the impact of the new coronavirus epidemic on the region's economy and accelerate the achievement of a resilient, sustainable and inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was hosted by Malaysia, the organizer of this year's APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting.
APEC Trade Ministers recognize the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment at this challenging time for economic recovery.
We commit to ensure that the emergency measures taken in response to the outbreak are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, do not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt global supply chains, while respecting World Trade Organization rules.
In his statement, the trade ministers of APEC members pledged to strengthen cooperation to facilitate the flow of goods and services necessary, promote connectivity by enhancing supply chain resilience, and minimizing disruptions to the flow of medical supplies, food and agricultural products to respond to the epidemic.
APEC trade ministers agreed on the need to discuss how to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict trade in essential goods and reiterated their commitment to facilitate the movement of people across borders without affecting the measures taken to stop the spread of the epidemic.
The Conference also issued a declaration on promoting the circulation of essential commodities.
The declaration said that economies will ensure that their trade measures in response to the epidemic are in line with WTO regulations, and commit to take action to reduce non-tariff trade barriers and trade promotion to promote the flow of goods necessary under the epidemic.
Malaysia's Minister of International Trade and Industry Azmin Ali, who chaired the meeting, said that despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia is committed to promoting the success of this year's APEC meeting, and the work of formulating the APEC cooperation vision after 2020 is progressing in an orderly manner.
Malaysia agreed to hold APEC-related meetings by video, but did not rule out the possibility of arranging physical meetings at the APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting at the end of the year.
