France to increase military investment in space - Xinhua
French Defense Minister Florence Parly said on the 24th that France will add hundreds of millions of euros to the space defense budget to develop space military forces to prevent other countries from making "unfriendly moves" in outer space.
Parly told the newspaper Provence on the same day that between 2019 and 2025, the budget for spending on France's space military program will increase from the previously proposed 3.6 billion euros (about 4.2 billion U.S. dollars) to 4.3 billion euros ($5 billion).
According to the French Military Planning Act 2019-2025 approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to update the existing observation satellites and communication satellites in the future, launch three electromagnetic listening satellites, and improve the modernization of space surveillance radars.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced in July last year that a military command of space and an “aeronautical and space force” would be set up within the French Air Force.
Parly said she would formally announce the creation of the Space Force when she visits a military academy in Saron, Provence.
Parly said the space force is part of the Air Force and will have a capacity of 500 by 2025.
“There is no longer any time that people thought space served the common good of science. Now space is a place where nations compete for global hegemony,” she said.
Parly reiterated Macron's previous statement, saying that the French side has no intention of provoking an arms race.
“We are not in an arms race by any means. But I have a responsibility to fully recognize the threats we may face.”
Parly repeated the surveillance of a French-Ukrainian military satellite in 2017.
She said the peep was a Russian satellite.
The Russian side denies this claim.
Parly said France would soon have small patrol satellites capable of detecting and locking "those black hands behind unfriendly moves."
French media believe that the reason why France sought to establish a space force was due to US President Donald Trump's request in February last year to the US Department of Defense to draft a space force bill.
In December, Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act into law, approving the creation of the sixth largest U.S. military service, the Space Force.
Some experts worry that the US moves have accelerated the pace of U.S. space militarization and could trigger a new space arms race.
