Three-year-old children's college playground play was smashed, and it made sense to complain to the school after being compensated?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author:Wang Sisuo Responsibility Editor:Wang Sisuo
The playground was smashed, and the child was compensated and then sued the school.
□ This reporter Zhao Yifan
When Xiao Wen, a 3-year-old playing in a university playground, he was accidentally hit by Chen of the softball team in the head while pitching.
After Chen's compensation, Mr. Wen, Xiao Wen's father, as Xiaowen's legal representative, sued the school to the court, demanding apologizing from the school where the incident occurred, and paying medical expenses, moral damage soothing funds for a total of 20,000 yuan.
Recently, the Beijing Haidian District People's Court held that after the trial of the case, the school set up a protective net in the playground at the time of the incident, had fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen had made compensation, according to which the judgment rejected the plaintiff's lawsuit.
Mr. Wen claimed that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiaowen to play in the school playground, when the softball team was training in the playground.
In order to avoid the risks involved, Xiao Wen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents operate in the safe area designated by the softball team.
However, after the softball team player Chen Mou took off his hand while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the guard to the above-mentioned safe area and hit the back of the small Wen.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with a head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that the facilities of the school stadium do not meet the relevant safety regulations and do not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The fault of the school led to the above-mentioned events, resulting in great physical and mental suffering, and also brought great pain to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In this regard, the school argued that the school has set up a protective net in the playground, and posted management regulations, training notices, told to enter the playground to maintain a safe distance from the training ground and remind themselves to be safe, and the plaintiff could not prove that the school "has not fulfilled its safety and security obligations", so it does not agree to compensation.
After the court hearing, it was found that the venue involved in the incident was a free venue for the public, and although the school had a security obligation for the management of the playground, this security obligation only needed to achieve the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground, and has fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen also compensated Xiao Wen for medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses of more than 2,000 yuan in accordance with the previous compensation agreement, and the two sides agreed to solve the dispute once and for all.
After the incident, Xiao Wen's parents once again claimed compensation from the school, and the court decided to reject all the plaintiff's application.
After the verdict, neither side appealed, and the sentence is now in force.
According to Article 37 of China's Tort Liability Law, the school, as a manager of a public place, has a security obligation; in the case of damage caused by the behavior of a third party, the third party bears the responsibility for tort, and the public place manager who fails to meet the safety and security obligations shall bear the corresponding supplementary liability.
The judge said that since, as the manager of a public place, it is most likely to understand the actual situation of the entire place, foresee the possible danger and damage, so that it is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of loss or the degree of damage, and the lowest cost of avoiding and mitigating the damage, the law stipulates that it bears the corresponding guarantee obligation to engage in social activities.
In this case, for persons who do not have a specific access population in a playground free of charge to the public, the school's security obligations should be commensurate with the social activities they engage in, in particular, the basic security measures should be taken and the obligation to inform the hidden danger.
In judicial practice, it is also not advisable to impose excessive security obligations on public places.
If the school has adopted the protective net and fulfilled the obligation to inform, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for third-party infringement, even if the administrators of public places such as schools do not meet their safety and security obligations, their liability is also as a supplement to damages, according to the newly promulgated Civil Code, the manager can also recover from the third party after assuming supplementary responsibilities.
