Israel strengthens repeated prevention and control of epidemic
2020-07-26 04:56:44 Source: Guangming Daily Author: Wang Sisuo Responsibility Editor: Wang Sisuo
Israel strengthens repeated epidemic prevention and control
At the beginning of the new crown pneumonia epidemic, Israel's prevention and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of prevention and control measures, the number of new crown pneumonia diagnoses in Israel has recently increased significantly, and the Israeli government has taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of new crown pneumonia was confirmed in Israel, in order to quickly close all entry and exit ports, suspend non-essential industries, change schools to online teaching, restrict public transportation and non-essential social activities, lock down cities with severe epidemics, and joint maintenance and control measures for military and police.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results, and by mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia in Israel fell to single digits in a single day.
With the control of the epidemic, Israel's prevention and control measures have been fully unsealed, and since June, the number of new confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia has gradually rebounded.
Especially after entering July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, Israel has had more than 1,500 new cases per day for eight days, and as of July 25, there were 916 new cases on the same day.
As of July 25, there were 59745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths in Israel.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has repeatedly taken emergency measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment venues, and introduced a policy to restrict public transportation, stipulating that each bus can not exceed 20 passengers.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of the "closed city" on weekends, which stipulates that the "closed city" will be implemented from 17:00 every Friday to 5 o'clock every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but shops, shopping centers, barbershops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while supermarkets, pharmacies and other basic services will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited on all dates and periods, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes will be banned from eating, and only take-away services will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people have not paid enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and have not been able to form a joint effort with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After the outbreak of the epidemic in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest because the government's prevention and control measures affected their own economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, believing that the anti-epidemic policy will affect the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands of protesters gathered in front of the official residence of Prime Minister Netanyahu in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's promulgation of preventive measures such as banning restaurants and cafes without corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people do not comply with the provisions of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters when they are outdoors, and in order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chins or hang them on their wrists.
During the repeated period of the epidemic, the school is the hardest hit area for the spread of the new coronavirus, and according to the reporter's recent visit to the kindergarten, the kindergarten teachers and students did not wear masks according to government requirements, and did not maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, laying a hidden danger for a large number of teachers and students infected with the virus.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the expert advisory team of the National Security Council to combat the epidemic, believes that Israel is moving towards a "dangerous situation", pointing out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough, and all leisure and entertainment venues and summer schools should be closed to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to fight the epidemic, and the Knesset and government departments should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, agree on the fight against the epidemic, and formulate clear steps including relevant restrictions in different departments.
